And I want to suggest four ways to transform our view of refugees.
These four perspectives share one thing in common: they incorporate opportunities of globalization, mobility, and markets, and modernize our way of thinking about the refugee problem.
The first idea is about favorable environments. This starts with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
With my colleagues from Oxford, we embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of refugees.
We chose Uganda, not because it represents all host countries.
It is exceptional.
Unlike most host countries, Uganda has provided an economic opportunity to refugees.
It gives them the right to work, the freedom to move.
And the results are extraordinary, for the refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we found discovered that 21% of refugees own a business employing people and 40% of these employees are nationals of the host country.
In other words, refugees create jobs for the citizens of the host country.
Even within the camps, we have discovered examples of dynamic and thriving businesses.
For example, in a village called Nakivale, we have the example of a Congolese refugee leading a business of digital music sharing.
We found a Rwandan who leads a company to enable young people to play video games on recycled consoles and televisions.
Despite the difficulties of extreme constraints, refugees innovate, and the man you see is a Congolese named Demou-Kay.
