The economist Alvin Roth has developed the concept of matching in, where the order of preference of the parties determines their potential correspondence.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym have sought ways to apply this idea to refugees, asking refugees to rank destinations, also allowing states to rank the type of refugee desired based on criteria such as skills or languages, then matching them.
Of course, we would need to implement quotas regarding diversity and vulnerability, but this is a way to increase the chances of matching.
The concept of matching is successfully applied, for example, in distributing students to universities, matching organ donors and patients, and the algorithm exists on dating sites.
Why not apply this to offer choice to refugees?
This could also be used at the national level where one of the biggest challenges is convincing local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to the city, which makes no sense.
Matching markets allow to gather these preferences and to hear the needs and requests of the host population and the refugees.
